Here are both approaches using Shell navigation and `IQueryAttributable`:

**1. Passing a simple string (product ID):**

```csharp
// ProductListPage.xaml.cs — navigate on tap
async void OnProductSelected(object sender, SelectionChangedEventArgs e)
{
    if (e.CurrentSelection.FirstOrDefault() is Product product)
        await Shell.Current.GoToAsync($"ProductDetailsPage?productId={product.Id}");
}
```

**2. Passing the full object:**

```csharp
async void OnProductSelected(object sender, SelectionChangedEventArgs e)
{
    if (e.CurrentSelection.FirstOrDefault() is Product product)
    {
        var navParams = new Dictionary<string, object>
        {
            { "product", product }
        };
        await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("ProductDetailsPage", navParams);
    }
}
```

> The single-parameter overload uses `string` query parameters (URL-encoded). The `Dictionary<string, object>` overload lets you pass complex objects without serialization.

**3. Receiving data via `IQueryAttributable` on the ViewModel:**

```csharp
public class ProductDetailsViewModel : ObservableObject, IQueryAttributable
{
    private string _productId;
    private Product _product;

    public string ProductId
    {
        get => _productId;
        set => SetProperty(ref _productId, value);
    }

    public Product Product
    {
        get => _product;
        set => SetProperty(ref _product, value);
    }

    public void ApplyQueryAttributes(IDictionary<string, object> query)
    {
        // Approach 1: simple string parameter
        if (query.TryGetValue("productId", out var id))
        {
            ProductId = id.ToString();
            // Load full product from a service, etc.
        }

        // Approach 2: full object parameter
        if (query.TryGetValue("product", out var obj) && obj is Product p)
        {
            Product = p;
            ProductId = p.Id;
        }
    }
}
```

**4. Wire the ViewModel to the page and register the route:**

```csharp
// ProductDetailsPage.xaml.cs
public ProductDetailsPage(ProductDetailsViewModel vm)
{
    InitializeComponent();
    BindingContext = vm;
}

// MauiProgram.cs or AppShell.xaml.cs
Routing.RegisterRoute("ProductDetailsPage", typeof(ProductDetailsPage));

// Also register in DI
builder.Services.AddTransient<ProductDetailsPage>();
builder.Services.AddTransient<ProductDetailsViewModel>();
```

**Key differences:**

| | String query param | `Dictionary<string, object>` |
|---|---|---|
| **Syntax** | `GoToAsync($"...?key={val}")` | `GoToAsync("...", dict)` |
| **Data types** | Strings only | Any object |
| **In `ApplyQueryAttributes`** | Value is `string` | Value is the original object |
| **Deep-link / URL support** | ✅ Yes | ❌ No |

Use the string approach when you only need an ID (and it supports deep links). Use the dictionary approach when you need to avoid a redundant lookup by passing the object you already have.
